Inside the loop, print i and j with a space in between and a newline. Then increment i and decrement j. 

Wait, the Python print statement adds a space between the two numbers and a newline. So in C, the printf should be "%d %d\n", i, j. Now, in C, variables need to be declared. So inside main, we have int n, i, j; Wait, but j is n*n. So after reading n, compute j as n * n. So putting it all together:

#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    int n;
    scanf("%d", &n); int i = 1;
    int j = n * n;
    while (i < j) {
        printf("%d %d\n", i, j);
        i++;
        j--;
    }
    return 0;
} Wait, but in C, variables should be declared at the beginning of the block unless using C99 or later. So maybe declare i and j after reading n. Because n needs to be read first. So:

int main() {
    int n;
    scanf("%d", &n);
    int i = 1;
    int j = n * n;
    // loop here
} Yes, that's okay.

C allows variables to be declared after statements if using C99. But sometimes people declare all variables at the top. But for clarity, maybe better to declare after reading n. But for compatibility, perhaps it's better to declare all variables at the top. Let me adjust:

int main() {
    int n, i, j;
    scanf("%d", &n);
    i = 1;
    j = n * n;
    // loop here
} Yes, this is compatible with older C standards. So the code structure is correct. Now, testing edge cases. For example, when n is 1. Then j is 1, so i is 1 and j is 1. The loop condition i < j is false, so nothing is printed. Which matches the Python code. Another case: n=2. Then j is 4. The loop runs while i < j. Let's see:

Initial i=1, j=4. Print 1 4. Then i becomes 2, j 3. Next iteration, i=2 < j=3: print 2 3. Then i becomes 3, j 2. Loop ends. So two lines. Which is correct. So the C code should work as intended. Another thing: make sure there are no off-by-one errors. The loop runs while i is less than j. So when i equals j, it stops. Which is the same as the Python code. Yes. So the translation looks correct. The main difference is the input handling and the print statement. Otherwise, the logic is the same.

